Across the arid waste her dismal way;

To the goal pressing, where the weary slave

May find a rest—a birthright claim—the grave!

“I confess again,” replied the Count with much suavi-

ty, “that I am somewhat at a loss to comprehend you;

pray, to what particulars of science do you allude?”

And the waving curls of her dark brown hair;
But the brook, nor the trees,
Nor the whispering breeze,
Could her feverish, tameless soul appease!
Now the wearying strife of her earthly life
Hath come to a final close;
She is gone where sorrow will never more
Disturb her soul’s repose;
Her heart was crushed,
And her lyre is hushed,
